  (The feature will be made after 1000 postcards or 1000 EMails :-)
@endnode


@node s_Introduction "Snap Introduction"
@prev s_Introduction

@{b} - Snap:@{ub}

    Not snapped yet ? Then try it and you`ll never miss it !
    It is something out of the cut and paste era.

Here a short description:

    With this Snap function you can frame a text on the screen and let the 
    computer type it for you multiple times. The framed text will be copied 
    to the clipboard and therefore a couple of other programs can insert this 
    text. To make this function working you must edit the @{"Hotkeys" link "fet_hotkeys" 0} 
    page and there you have to edit the 'Snap' and 'Insert Clipboard' hotkeys. 
    Please be sure that you assign only a key to the 'Snap' hotkey, because the 
    mouseclick with the left mousebutton will be internally added.

@endnode

@node s_Features "Snap Features"
@prev s_Features

MCP snap combines the POWER of Powersnap with the SPEED of the good old snap.
Actually it features:

-snapping of fonts with a width <= 16 and ysize <1024
-snapping of text that is directly written on a picture (try DPaint) see @{colorsnap link s_colsnap}
-snapping of bold/underlined/invers/changing colors
-first snap to handle small letters at the first click (try snapping a single dot)
-geniously configurable
-snapping on screens >8 bit
-optional try all nonprop fonts in memory
-optional try user specified fonts beside the rastports default font
@endnode

@node s_Requirements "Snap Requirements"
@prev s_Requirements

You need an Amiga with OS2.0 or higher.
I suggest using this snap with 68020+ due to 68020 optimized ASM routines.
@endnode

@node s_Configuration "Snap Configuration"
@prev s_Configuration

@{b}Font-List:@{ub}

Snap will try all fonts in this (in the given order) list after the rastports 
default font. You should insert your mainly used fonts there.
Note that only opened fonts will be tried. So a long list must not mean a longer 
snapping time. (Except snapping fails and you have got a lot of fonts in memory).


@{b}Colorsnap:@{ub}

Enable snapping of text over pictures. That means if there are more than 2 colors
in in the area of a single character snap will try color after color until a character is
recognized or no color is left. You should enable this only on fast machines (68030+).
I needed it to snap the icon text on my WB.
Note that colourful ANSIS can be snapped without enabling this switch.


@{b}Extend Area:@{ub}

If you release your LMB while snapping and then go on selecting, the selected
area will extend. Otherwise one edge is fixed on the first clicked character.


@{b}Try all fonts:@{ub}

Snap will try all opened fonts after the rastports default font and the fonts
specified in the fontlist.


@{b}No Displaybeep:@{ub}

Snap won`t beep if no character was recognized.


@{b}EOL Errorskip:@{ub}

Snap will kill all unrecognized characters at the end of each line.


@{b}Try bold fonts:@{ub}

Snap will try bold fonts too (after the normal-styled fonts).
Note that you need to click on a normal-styled character first. If you want snap
to recognize bold characters at first see Try bold fonts first.

@{b}Try bold fonts first:@{ub}

Snap will try bold fonts,after all fonts in all colors have been tried.


@{b}Error sign:@{ub}

The character that will be inserted for an unrecognized token.


@{b}Snap Mode:@{ub}

Here you can configure how snap behaves when clicking:

-Normal    first click: a square area is selected
           doubleclick: a word is selected
           next  click: a full line is selected
           next clicks cycle between these modes

-Area Snap first click: a word is selected
           next  click: a full line is selected
           next  click: a square area is selected
           next clicks cycle between these modes

-Line Snap first click: a full line is selected
           next  click: a square area is selected
           next click: a word is selected
           next clicks cycle between these modes


@{b}Crawling direction:@{ub}

Configures the direction of the crawling ants (left or right).


@{b}Crawling speed:@{ub}

0= no movement
1-7=crawling speed (the higher the faster)


@{b}Pen:@{ub}

The color of crawling ants (usually pen 0=black
                                    pen 1=white
                                    pen 2=blue)


@{b}Snap pattern:@{ub}

The pattern of the crawling ants (3333 is a good idea).

@endnode

